with support from their first husband. “Breaking the union and abandoning a wife are seen as the last extreme measure,” according to Makunda (1999). Kementz (2006) argued that if women want “compatibility in their marriages and family obligations they decided to reconcile with older husbands and support them through old age.” Sometimes they return to their first life partners. The elders in the Somali clan tradition “initiate arbitration by encouraging a couple to reconcile if there is a possibility of doing so” (Kementz, 2006, p. 18). Breaking up a marriage is very rare as it usually results in a conflicting environment within the community. The divorce rate in Sonaliland does not significantly differ from the divorce rate in the United States (Kementz, 2006).
In some cases the women do reconcile with their husbands; in others they choose to get divorced. When reentered as a previously divorced wife, she is banned from the old family, thus difficult to integrate further into the new family.
